The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Whirlpool to upgrade plants

 A STAFF REPORTER

 Tamal Kanti Saha in Calcutta on Wednesday. A Telegraph picture

 Calcutta, April 11: Whirlpool of India Ltd will invest $20 million to make its plants capable of producing more high-end products. The company also expects to clock a net profit this fiscal.

 For the nine-month period of April to December 2006, Whirlpool of India posted an operating profit of Rs 44.21 crore against Rs 2.18 crore in the same period of the previous year. The companys turnover was Rs 1,245 crore.

 Whirlpool is focusing on India. We will invest $20 million by the middle of 2008 to upgrade facilities at Faridabad, Pune and Pondicherry. We also expect a growth of 20 per cent this fiscal, said Tamal Kanti Saha, vice-president (sales), Whirlpool of India.

 The companys accumulated losses is Rs 104.8 crore. However, the forecast of higher earnings in the coming years will help the company pay back the debt, Saha said.

 Already the working capital as a percentage of the turnover is down to 3.5 per cent from 10.5 per cent. 

 Whirlpool is also looking at product re-engineering.

 Whirlpool of Indias advertising budget is Rs 70 crore, which includes publicity for the companys new product range.

 A marginal hike in prices is expected, especially for high-end products, with energy efficiency certification becoming mandatory by June.

 The company also hopes to cross the Rs 1500-crore mark in turnover. 




